# Tauri Build Verification

After any task that touches `src-tauri/`, Tauri commands, scheduler/native services, or frontend code wired to `invoke`, run a release build before finishing:

```bash
npm run build:tauri
```

If the full bundle is too slow for a quick check, at minimum run:

```bash
npm run build && cargo build --release --manifest-path src-tauri/Cargo.toml
```

## Fix and scan for similar issues

When the build fails or emits Rust warnings, fix the reported issue and scan nearby code for the same pattern.

### Rust `private_interfaces` (common)

Do not expose a `pub`/`pub(crate)` method that returns a private enum or struct. Prefer keeping the helper on the module:

```rust
// ❌ BAD — private enum leaks through public method
enum SchedulerStartOutcome { Started, AlreadyRunning }
impl FeedSchedulerState {
    pub fn start(...) -> Result<SchedulerStartOutcome, String> { ... }
}

// ✅ GOOD — method stays module-private; commands call it
impl FeedSchedulerState {
    fn start(...) -> Result<SchedulerStartOutcome, String> { ... }
}
```

Alternative: mark the return type `pub(crate)` only when the API must stay public.

Use `pub(crate) fn` when another module in `src-tauri` must call the helper (for example `lib.rs` exit hooks calling `FeedSchedulerState::stop`).

### Other patterns to check in the same pass

- Missing Cargo features (`tokio/macros`, `reqwest/stream`, etc.) after adding async/stream APIs
- Tauri command names/types out of sync with `src/lib/tauriClient/`
- TypeScript errors from `tsc` in the `beforeBuildCommand` step
- New `pub` items in `lib.rs` that surface private helper types

## Done criteria

- `npm run build:tauri` exits 0 with no Rust warnings
- Scheduler/native tests still pass when the changed area has coverage (`npm test`, `npm run test:rust`)
